daily_counts <- time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
      filter (Country_Region == "US")

p <- ggplot(daily_counts, aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
        geom_point() +
        ggtitle("Confirmed COVID-19 Cases") +
# gganimate lines  
        geom_point(aes(group = seq_along(Date))) +
        transition_reveal(Date) 

# make the animation
 anim_save("daily_counts_US.gif", p)
 animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)

p <- time_series_deaths_long |>
  filter (Country_Region %in% c("US","Canada", "Mexico","Brazil","Egypt","Ecuador","India", "Netherlands", "Germany", "China" )) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=Country_Region, y=Confirmed, color= Country_Region)) + 
    geom_point(aes(size=Confirmed)) + 
    transition_time(Date) + 
    labs(title = "Cumulative Deaths: {frame_time}") + 
    ylab("Deaths") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))

animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)

5.2.1 Exercises

For each of the sample tables, describe what each observation and each column represents.

Code 
#Table 1
#Wide format, one row per country year. Represents a singke country in a specific year
#Columns: Country( the name of the country) Year(the year of oberservation) Cases(The number of reported cases)Population(The population of that country in that year)

#Table 2
#Long format, one row per country year variable.
#Each obersvation is a singlle measurement for a given country and year.
#Columns: Country( the name of the country) Year(the year of oberservation) Cases(The number of reported cases)Population(The population of that country in that year)

#Table 3
#Detived format, one rown per ountry year with calculated rate.
#Each oberservation is a countru and year pair with the rate expressed as a string.
#Columns: Country( the name of the country) Year(the  year of oberservation) Rate(The rate expression)

2-Sketch out the process youâd use to calculate the rate for table2 and table3. You will need to perform four operations:

Extract the number of TB cases per country per year.

Extract the matching population per country per year.

Divide cases by population, and multiply by 10000.

Store back in the appropriate place.

Code 
#Table 2

# Step 1: Extract the number of TB cases per country per year.
cases <- table2 %>%
  filter(type == "cases") %>%
  select(country, year, cases = count)

# Step 2: Extract the mathcung population per country per year.
population <- table2 %>%
  filter(type == "population") %>%
  select(country, year, population = count)

# Step 3: Divide cases by population, and multipy by 10000
rates <- left_join(cases, population, by = c("country", "year")) %>%
  mutate(rate = (cases / population) * 10000)

# Step 4: store back in the appropiate plcae
# Final result stored in 'rates'
rates

#Table 3

# Step 1: Extract the number of TB cases per country per year.

cases <- table3 %>%
  separate(rate, into = c("cases", "population"), sep = "/", convert = TRUE) %>%
  select(country, year, cases)

# Step 2: Extract the mathcung population per country per year.

population <- table3 %>%
  separate(rate, into = c("cases", "population"), sep = "/", convert = TRUE) %>%
  select(country, year, population)

# Step 3: Divide cases by plibrary(tidyverse)

rates <- left_join(cases, population, by = c("country", "year")) %>%
  mutate(rate = (cases / population) * 10000)

# Step 4: store back in the appropiate plcae
# Final result stored in 'rates'

2-Instead of making a graph of 5 countries on the same graph as in the above example, use facet_wrap with scales="free_y".

Code 
time_series_confirmed_long |> 
  group_by(Country_Region, Date) |> 
  summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) |> 
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("China", "France", "Italy", "Korea, South", "US")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Confirmed)) +
    geom_line(color="purple") +
    facet_wrap(~ Country_Region, scales = "free_y") +
    ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases by Country")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Country_Region'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.

3-Using the daily count of confirmed cases, make a single graph with 5 countries of your choosing.

Code 
time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("India", "Germany", "Brazil", "South Africa", "US")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("Daily COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

4-Plot the cumulative deaths in the US, Canada and Mexico (you will need to download time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv)

Code 
time_series_deaths_long |> 
  group_by(Country_Region, Date) |> 
  summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) |> 
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("US", "Canada", "Mexico")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Confirmed, color = Country_Region)) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("Cumulative COVID-19 Deaths")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Country_Region'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.

5-Make a graph with the countries of your choice using the daily deaths data

Code 
time_series_deaths_daily <- time_series_deaths_long |> 
  group_by(Country_Region, Date) |> 
  summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) |> 
  mutate(Daily = Confirmed - lag(Confirmed, default = first(Confirmed)))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Country_Region'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.
Code 
time_series_deaths_daily |> 
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("India", "Brazil", "Germany", "Mexico", "US", "Argentina", "South Africa")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(title = "Daily COVID-19 Deaths",
         x = "Date",
         y = "Deaths") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

6-Make an animation of your choosing (do not use a graph with geom_smooth)

Code 
daily_deaths_latin_america <- time_series_deaths_daily |> 
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("Mexico", "Brazil", "Ecuador", "Argentina", "Chile"))

p <- ggplot(daily_deaths_latin_america, aes(x = Date, y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) +
  geom_point(aes(group = seq_along(Date))) +
  ggtitle("Daily COVID-19 Deaths in Latin America") +
  transition_reveal(Date)

animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)
anim_save("daily_deaths_latin_america.gif",p)
